Iterator Interface in Java

Iterator is an interface in Java used to traverse (iterate over) elements in a collection.

It is part of the Java Collection Framework and works with classes like ArrayList, LinkedList, HashSet, etc.

Why use Iterator?

Iterator is useful when:

you need a safe way to iterate
you want to remove elements during iteration
you want a unified way to work with different collections
Creating an Iterator
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Iterator;

ArrayList<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Apple");
list.add("Banana");

Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
Main Methods of Iterator
hasNext()
it.hasNext();
returns true if there are more elements
used to control the loop
next()
it.next();
returns the next element
moves the iterator forward
remove()
it.remove();
removes the last element returned by next()
safe way to remove elements during iteration
Example: Iterating with Iterator
Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();

while (it.hasNext()) {
    String item = it.next();
    System.out.println(item);
}
Example: Removing Elements Safely
Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();

while (it.hasNext()) {
    String item = it.next();
    
    if (item.startsWith("A")) {
        it.remove(); // safe removal
    }
}

👉 Important: do NOT use list.remove() inside a loop — it can cause errors.

Common Mistake

❌ Wrong way:

for (String item : list) {
    if (item.startsWith("A")) {
        list.remove(item); // can throw ConcurrentModificationException
    }
}

✔ Correct way: use Iterator.remove()

Iterator vs forEach
Iterator	for-each loop
Can remove elements	Cannot safely remove
More control	Simpler syntax
Works step-by-step	Works automatically
Important Notes
Iterator works only forward
each element can be accessed once
calling next() without hasNext() may throw exception
not thread-safe
Summary
Iterator is used to loop through collections
main methods: hasNext(), next(), remove()
safest way to remove elements during iteration
gives more control than for-each

